title: A high-resolution study of isobaric analogue resonances in 41K

x4freetext: A high-resolution study of isobaric analogue
resonances in 41K

x4codes.hlp: Duke University, Durham, NC, United States of America
Duke University, Durham, NC, United States of America

x4freetext: The effective energy spread in the proton beam itself,
in the most favourable cases observed, is 153 eV,
before correcting for target thickness, Doppler
broadening and the natural width of the resonance.
Generally, our total resolution was about 200-250 eV.
The detector is at an angle of 135 degrees to
the incident beam. The solid angle subtended in this
arrangement is about 15 msr.
Argon target is on the order of 50 eV thick,
operating temperature of 60 degrees K was chosen.
Figures with differential cross sections of
40Ar(p,p)40Ar and 40Ar(p,alpha)37Cl at 135 degrees at
incident proton energies of from 1.63 to 2.60 MeV
and 40Ar(p,n)40K at 20 degrees at incident proton
energies of from 2.34 to 2.60 MeV (Figs. 4-7)
are given in the article, but the quality of the copy
available to the compiler is so bad that their
digitising is not possible.

x4freetext: No information on source of uncertainty.
Relative energies of resonances are accurate to 0.3 keV
or better. The partial width for proton capture has
been neglected in this analysis.
The proton widths range in precision
from about 10% on the widest resonances to about 40% on
the very weakest ones.
